abstract = {Energy and water limitations of tree growth remain insufficiently understood at large spatiotemporal scales, hindering model representation of interannual or longer-term ecosystem processes. By assessing and statistically scaling the climatic drivers from 2710 tree-ring sites, we identified the boreal and temperate land areas where tree growth during 1930{\{}$\backslash$textendash{\}}1960 CE responded positively to temperature (20.8 {\{}$\backslash$textpm{\}} 3.7 Mio km2; 25.9 {\{}$\backslash$textpm{\}} 4.6{\%}), precipitation (77.5 {\{}$\backslash$textpm{\}} 3.3 Mio km2; 96.4 {\{}$\backslash$textpm{\}} 4.1{\%}), and other parameters. The spatial manifestation of this climate response is determined by latitudinal and altitudinal temperature gradients, indicating that warming leads to geographic shifts in growth limitations. We observed a significant (P {\textless} 0.001) decrease in temperature response at cold-dry sites between 1930{\{}$\backslash$textendash{\}}1960 and 1960{\{}$\backslash$textendash{\}}1990 CE, and the total temperature-limited area shrunk by -8.7 {\{}$\backslash$textpm{\}} 0.6 Mio km2. Simultaneously, trees became more limited by atmospheric water demand almost worldwide. These changes occurred under mild warming, and we expect that continued climate change will trigger a major redistribution in growth responses to climate.},
